Take-home exercises can be a reasonable choice and are closer to real-world examples, provided that:

- The exercise makes clear exactly what the criteria is
- It is reasonably scoped to 30min/1hr
- It's universally accessible (runs on @gitpod or similar)

There are so many ways to vet someone other than "do this cookie-cutter exercise." It's probably the least useful way to verify someone's experience.

Some alternatives:
- Pair programming, on a challenge of candidate's choice
- Talking to someone, maybe

This requires breaking work down into actionable steps, a decent CI/CD pipeline, solid engineering team culture. There's a lot of variables here.

It's counter-intuitive but sometimes waiting and seeing work through is more efficient than picking up another task (see num2)

3. Lots of in-flight work

This one is inevitable, especially in certain environments (start-ups, consulting, etc)

Optimize for quick completion on tasks. The quicker I can go from dev -> PR review -> accepted PR in staging, the better off I am.

One way to tackle this is clarifying up front w/ your team! It makes it easier to collaborate with them on priorities, whether it's worth losing a chunk of time or whether it can wait.

Scheduling specific times where you are coming up for air helps too!

2. Task switching 🔀

There is no multi-tasking for me. There's a cost to task switching for all folks, but for me it can't be overstated just how much time is lost to task switching.

There's an emotional cost to finally gaining momentum, only to be asked to pull out of that.

I set out to build a bunch of moving boxes, but then I ended up learning a lot about the formula for pyramidal numbers, because I couldn't just STACK them like normal boxes. https://t.co/dIAHiBgQxE

This is why it's worthwhile to build your own throwaway apps:

Read the docs to get a breadth of knowledge, follow along with all the best practices.

Then try and build something else real fast, figure out the pain points in it. Figure out your knowledge gaps then fill them

Realizing through putting moving boxes together that my learning process is:

1. Do it slow and right
2. Do it fast and wrong
3. Analyze
4. Do it fast and right

Which boils down to the phases of Learn > Gain Experience > Reflect > Refine

It's not enough to assemble a bunch of bankers boxes. I need to be able to assemble them in record time.
